#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:23
msgid "A few important notes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:25
msgid ""
"This class is meant to be used as a base-class widget for doing VTK "
"rendering in Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:28
msgid ""
"In VTK (and C++) there is a very important distinction between public ivars "
"(attributes in pythonspeak), protected ivars, and private ivars.  When you "
"write a python class that you want to 'look and feel' like a VTK class, you "
"should follow these rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:33
msgid ""
"Attributes should never be public.  Attributes should always be either "
"protected (prefixed with a single underscore) or private (prefixed with a "
"double underscore).  You can provide access to attributes through public Set/"
"Get methods (same as VTK)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:38
msgid ""
"Use a single underscore to denote a protected attribute, e.g. self."
"_RenderWindow is protected (can be accessed from this class or a derived "
"class)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:42
msgid ""
"Use a double underscore to denote a private attribute, e.g. self.__InExpose "
"cannot be accessed outside of this class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../Wrapping/Python/vtkmodules/tk/vtkTkRenderWidget.py:45
msgid ""
"All attributes should be 'declared' in the __init__() function i.e. set to "
"some initial value.  Don't forget that 'None' means 'NULL' - the python/vtk "
"wrappers guarantee their equivalence."
msgstr ""

